Task 1¶

Read Chapter 1-3 of Fundamentals of Data Visualizations, then answer the questions below.

Question 1.1¶

Describe the visualization concept scales.

Answer 1.1¶

Your answer here

A scale defines a unique mapping between data and aesthetics. Importantly, a scale must be one-to-one, such that for each specific data value there is exactly one aesthetics value and vice versa. If a scale isn't one-to-one, then the data visualization becomes ambiguous.

Question 1.2¶

In Figures 2.3 and 2.4 the same data is visualized in two different ways. Discuss the pros and cons of the two approaches. Which one do you prefer and why?

Answer 1.2¶

Your answer here

Figure 2.3 can show the temperature change between month intervals but it can't present the precise temperature for a particular month. Figure 2.4 can show the temperature of each month but it can't show the temperature change between months. I would prefer figure 2.3 because it is more clean in terms of color.

Question 1.3¶

Describe situations when nonlinear axes might be useful. When should they not be used?

Answer 1.3¶

Your answer here

Nonlinear axes is useful when the data set contains numbers of very different magnitudes. Then, they may need nonlinear scales to show the ratios. They should not be used when the variables have a linear relationship. Then, linear scales can provide an accurate representation of the data.

Question 1.4¶

In which situations could a polar coordinate system be useful?

Answer 1.4¶

Your answer here

Polar coordinates can be useful for data of a periodic nature, such that data values at one end of the scale can be logically joined to data values at the other end.

Question 3.2¶

In Lecture2 I used boxplots, error-bars, and violin plots to visualize fluctuations in winter temperature in Västerås. Now using the weather data above plot the temperature per month (like in Fig. 9.8 here) using error-bars, boxplots and violin plots with data points. For each month plot the temperature for 2009 and 2010 next to each other (see example on webpage).

In [93]:
# Insert code here using standard error
eb = pd.DataFrame({"month": [],
                   "year": [],
                   "mean": [],
                   "sd": []})
month = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
year = ['Temp2009', 'Temp2010']
for i in month:
    for j in year:
        x = tidy_data.query("(month == @i) and (variable == @j)")
        #df = pd.concat([df, pd.DataFrame({"month": i, "year": j, "mean": np.mean(x.value), "sd": np.std(x.value)})])
        eb.loc[len(eb.index)] = [i, j, np.mean(x.value), np.std(x.value)] 

p = (ggplot(eb, aes(fct_inorder(eb["month"]), "mean"))
    + geom_point(aes(color = "year"), position = position_dodge(0.3)) 
    + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = "mean - sd", ymax = "mean + sd", color="year"), position=position_dodge(0.3), width=0.2)
    + labs(y = "Temperature", x = "month", title="Temperature for 2009 and 2010")
    + scale_fill_manual(values = cbPalette, name="Year") 
    + theme_minimal())

p

Briefly discuss the drawback with each approach (standard errors, boxplots, and violin plots).

Write answer here

For standard errors, it is not obvious what the points and error bars represent. This may confuse the readers.

For boxplots, it is hard to observe the detailed shape of distribution.

For violin plots, the quantitative value for the mean is not provided.

Question 4.2¶

Often we want to highlight a specific column in a barplot. Using the same layout as in the most recent plot highlight the column of Jumanji in orange, and keep the remaining columns grey.

In [101]:
# Insert code here 
movies = movies.assign(
            highlight = lambda dataframe: dataframe['Title'].map(lambda title: True if title == "Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle" else False) 
            )
p = (ggplot(movies, aes("Title", "Weekend_gross", fill= "highlight")) 
  + geom_bar(stat="identity", width = 0.5, position = position_dodge(0.7))
  + geom_text(aes(label = "Weekend_gross"))
  + labs(x = "Movies", y = "Weekend gross")
  + scale_x_discrete(limits=pos[::-1],expand = (0, 0.4))
  + coord_flip()
  + scale_fill_manual( values = ["grey", "orange"], guide = False )
  + theme_minimal()
  + theme(axis_text_x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=0.1), 
          legend_position="none"))
p
